{"source_key":"sha256-1f182aec97e74c799418946c45b6cf73","record_index":254,"record_hash":"sha256:f1787460de78c64eb489ccb7ecdc3c29272b23b0e400fa39441e83c77b9e23ab","timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:41:59.788Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: df410a\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2250\nOutput:\n# Agent Trail\n\nAgent Trail is the review-adjacent product surface for captured agent sessions.\nIt is the page a reviewer opens from a pull request to understand the agent work\nbehind a change.\n\n## Working Name\n\nUse **Agent Trail** for now.\n\nGood PR link text:\n\n- View Agent Trail\n- Explore Agent Trail\n- Agent Trail for this PR\n\nAvoid names like \"transcript\", \"audit log\", or \"provenance report\" for the\nproduct surface. The page may contain transcript records and provenance facts,\nbut the user-facing promise is simpler: follow the useful trail behind this\nchange.\n\n## Product Shape\n\nA developer opens a pull request from GitButler or GitHub. GitButler adds a link\nto the pull request. A reviewer clicks that link and lands on a GitButler-owned\nweb page for the Agent Trail.\n\nThe page lets the reviewer explore captured agent context related to the pull\nrequest:\n\n- prompts and requests from the human\n- assistant responses and claims\n- tool calls and tool results\n- tests and validation attempts\n- decisions and tradeoffs\n- follow-up questions\n- edge cases discussed or missed\n\nThis is not primarily a chat transcript viewer. The transcript is the source of\ntruth, but the review experience should be organized around helping a reviewer\nunderstand the change.\n\n## Core Question\n\nAgent Trail should answer:\n\n> What agent context helps me review this pull request?\n\nIt should not claim:\n\n> This agent session authored this pull request.\n\nThe language should stay evidence-based. Say that a session or turn is related\nto a pull request, branch, review, or change. Do not present related agent data\nas proof of authorship.\n\n## Current Decisions\n\n- MVP entry point: on-demand URL replacement.\n- Shareable page shape: generated snapshot, not a live view.\n- Initial access scope: public repositories and public metadata only.\n- Likely host: Forge, outside the GitButler repository.\n- Data interpretation: server-side code links and uses `bu\n[TRUNCATED]\nded transcript hydration\n- optional PR-link creation metadata\n\nThe hosted Agent Trail product should live outside this repository. The likely\nhome is `/Users/kiril/src/forge`, if the current product direction holds.\n\nForge should own the review product concerns:\n\n- hosted routes and stable URLs\n- authentication and permissions\n- publication flow\n- PR link landing page\n- review-specific ranking and highlighting\n- generated summaries, if added\n- retention and visibility policy\n\nThe boundary should be a small Agent Trail projection or lookup contract, not a\nsecond implementation of `but-agentlog` inside Forge. GitButler records related\nagent evidence; Forge publishes review-safe Agent Trails.\n\nThe server side of the Agent Trail application is expected to use the\n`but-agentlog` crate to interact with captured data. It should call\n`but-agentlog` read/query/projection primitives rather than reimplementing\nGitMeta key parsing, transcript normalization, target verification, or bounded\nrecord hydration.\n\nEven if the Agent Trail application lives in another repository, it should link\nthe real `but-agentlog` code somehow.\n\nPossible linkage paths:\n\n- short term: depend on the GitButler repository as a pinned Cargo git\n  dependency and import the `but-agentlog` package\n- local development: use a path dependency from Forge to a local GitButler\n  checkout\n- longer term: make `but-agentlog` publishable, or split a smaller\n  `but-agentlog` read/projection crate if the full GitButler workspace\n  dependency graph is too heavy\n\nExample shape:\n\n```toml\nbut-agentlog = { git = \"https://github.com/gitbutlerapp/gitbutler.git\", rev = \"<pinned-revision>\", package = \"but-agentlog\" }\n```\n\nThe important rule is no copied reader logic. Forge may own Agent Trail\npublication and UI policy, but the canonical storage interpretation should stay\nin `but-agentlog`.\n\nThis is still a design-phase decision. Do not start implementing the Forge\nsurface until the publication boundary and permissions model are clearer.\n\n## Server-Side Metadata Fetch\n\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:41:59.788Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}